`.setex()` is for string. what you&#39;re passing there is object. if you want to use string data type in redis, you will have to pass a String to it by `JSON.stringify(temp)` and `JSON.parse` when you get it back from redis.

```js
redisClient.setex(item._id, 3600, JSON.stringify(temp), (err, data) =&gt; {
    if (err) {
        reject(err)
    } else {
        resolve(data)
    }
})

```

redis has a data type that is similar to object which is [hash](https://redis.io/commands#hash) but this only works if your object is shallow.

```js
redis.hmset(&#39;item:${item._id}&#39;, item) // saving
redis.hgetall(&#39;item:1&#39;) // geting all fiellds out
redis.hmget(&#39;item:1&#39;, [&#39;field1&#39;, &#39;field2&#39;]) // geting some fields out
```

usage is different for each library but the idea is like this

[![enter image description here][1]][1]


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/Z1zG8.png

